Relations Between the Races of Aetheria
In the current age, open, large-scale wars between the major racial powers are rare. The endless internal conflicts within each race, combined with the constant pressure from demonic incursions, leave little room for grand racial crusades. Yet beneath this fragile surface peace lies a deep, poisonous undercurrent of mistrust, old grudges, and raw hatred. Xenophobia runs strong in every culture. Raids across borders are commonplace. Slavery is an accepted fact of life — prisoners of war, raid captives, debt slaves, and those born into bondage fill the markets of nearly every kingdom and hold. Trade exists, but it is usually conducted through heavily guarded neutral zones or by greedy intermediaries who care more for profit than blood.
Humans and Elves
Relations are cool at best, openly hostile at worst. Many humans view elves as arrogant, long-lived snobs who hoard knowledge and look down on “mayfly” races. Elves, in turn, see humans as reckless, destructive children who breed like vermin and desecrate the land.
Limited trade occurs (elven herbs, dyes, and magical reagents for human metals and grains), but it is heavily restricted. Raids are frequent on both sides — human bandits or rogue March lords sometimes strike elven border groves, while Wildwood Exiles occasionally raid human settlements for “sacrifices” or revenge. Slavery is common: captured humans are sometimes kept as laborers or curiosities in elven enclaves, while elves taken in raids are often sold in human black markets as possible wives for nobles (that believe introducing elven blood to the house will produce more mages in the future of the house), as mages, or as sex slaves.

Humans and Dwarves
This is one of the more pragmatic relationships, though still tainted by deep-seated prejudice. Dwarves consider most humans greedy, short-sighted, and dishonorable. Humans view dwarves as stubborn, miserly cave-dwellers who overcharge for their superior craftsmanship.
Trade is relatively active (dwarven weapons, armor, and engineering for human foodstuffs, textiles, and mercenaries). Several human kingdoms maintain permanent embassies in Karad-Dur. However, border skirmishes and raids still occur, especially over mining rights in the foothills. Dwarven captives are rare but valuable as master smiths; human slaves are sometimes worked to death in the more brutal deep holds.

Humans and Beastkin
Highly volatile and often violent. Many humans see Beastkin as savage half-animals — useful as gladiators, shock troops, or cheap labor, but barely civilized. Beastkin view humans as invasive weaklings who destroy ancestral hunting grounds and treat them like beasts.
Beastkin tribes frequently raid human border villages and caravans, while human March lords launch “pacification” expeditions into savannah lands. Slavery is extremely common here: Beastkin captives are a major commodity in human arenas and labor camps, especially strong Lionfolk or Wolf packs. The prettier Catfolk, Foxfolk and Rabbitfolk are usually used for sex slaves and some nobles are fascinated by them and mix their noble houses bloodline with these beastkin. Some human kingdoms maintain “tame” Beastkin clans as vassals or auxiliary troops, but these arrangements are fragile and breed resentment.

Elves and Dwarves
Ancient and bitter rivalry. The old philosophical divide (elves see dwarves as defilers of nature; dwarves see elves as useless dreamers) has never faded. Trade is minimal and conducted mostly through human intermediaries. Raids are uncommon but exceptionally vicious when they occur, usually over contested mountain-forest borders.
Both races occasionally enslave the other, though they consider it deeply shameful. Most elves and dwarves would rather die than be taken alive by the other.

Elves and Beastkin
Generally better than most relations, but still strained. High Forest elves respect Beastkin’s connection to nature and often ally with them against demonic incursions. However, they view most Beastkin as primitive and volatile. Wildwood Exiles have much closer (and bloodier) ties with Beastkin tribes.
Raids still happen over hunting grounds and sacred sites. Slavery exists but is less common than in human lands — captured Beastkin are more often “re-educated” into elven service or ritually sacrificed.

Dwarves and Beastkin
Pragmatic but distant. Dwarves respect the raw strength and endurance of certain Beastkin (especially Ironhide Clans), and sometimes hire them as mercenaries for deep expeditions. However, they generally consider Beastkin unreliable and too emotional. Beastkin see dwarves as cold, greedy stone-hoarders.
Raids are rare due to geography, but when they happen they are brutal. Slavery flows both ways in small numbers, usually captured warriors pressed into service.

All Races and Demons
This is the one area of relative (if uneasy) unity. Almost every mortal race hates demons with a burning passion. Even so, pragmatism and corruption create exceptions:

Some human March lords and merchant houses engage in forbidden trade with Highblood demons.
Certain Serpentis Beastkin clans and Wildwood Exiles maintain shadowy pacts.
A few radical dwarven and elven factions have been known to bargain with demons in desperate times.

Demons themselves treat all mortal races as prey, though they take special pleasure in breaking elves and Beastkin. Slavery under demonic rule is nightmarish — souls are as valuable as bodies in the infernal territories.

General Atmosphere
Xenophobia is deeply ingrained. Most villages and cities are racially homogeneous; mixed settlements are rare and usually tense. Travelers of other races are often met with suspicion, higher prices, or outright hostility. Interracial marriage is extremely rare and usually results in exile or death in more traditional societies.
Individual, or small parties travelling and or dealing in other races territories are mostly ignored as vagrants passing through.
Bards sing of ancient alliances during the Golden Age, but in practice, every race keeps one eye on its neighbors even while fighting demons. Betrayal is expected. Temporary alliances form and shatter with the seasons.
In this broken world, the greatest threat may not be the demons themselves — but the inability of the mortal races to stand together even against extinction.
